                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/2855: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-03T21:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 3, 1940—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 3—5:52 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1018. With reference to the French offer to discuss immediately any and all
                    Italian claims against France (see my telegram No. 964, May 31, 10 a.m.),
                    François-Poncet informed the French Government that Ciano had said to him that
                    Mussolini would not be interested in receiving any French territories by
                    peaceful negotiations. He had decided to make war on France. There would,
                    therefore, be no reply to the French note.</p>
                <p>Is it impossible for the President now to speak the truth in public about
                    Mussolini?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
